Corpus Transformation

In this section, the dataset is made into a Corpus and then cleaned to provide a better sample set. This includes removing:

1-Replace Contraction 2-Remove Punctuation 3-Uncapitalizing words 4-Removing Numbers 5-Replace Abbreviation 6-Replace Symbol 7-Remove Stopwords 8-Remove Space

sample_data_c <- VCorpus(VectorSource(sample_data))
removeURL<-function(x) gsub("http[[:alnum:]]*","",x)
removeSign<-function(x) gsub("[[:punct:]]","",x)
removeNum<-function(x) gsub("[[:digit:]]","",x)
removeapo<-function(x) gsub("'","",x)
removeNonASCII<-function(x) iconv(x, "latin1", "ASCII", sub="")
removerepeat<- function(x) gsub("([[:alpha:]])\\1{2,}", "\\1\\1", x)
toLowerCase <- function(x) sapply(x,tolower)
removeSpace<-function(x) gsub("\\s+"," ",x)
removeTh<-function(x) gsub(" th", "",x)
clean_corpus <- function(corpus){
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removeapo))#remove apostrophe
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removeNum))#remove numbers
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removeURL)) #remove web url
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removeSign)) #remove number and punctuation except apostrophe
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removeNonASCII)) #remove non-ASCII
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(toLowerCase))# convert uppercase to lowercase
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removerepeat))# remove repeated alphabets in a words
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,removeWords,c(stopwords("english"), "bv", "e","b","c","d","ha","blah")) #remove common english words and letters
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removeTh)) #remove th from words
     corpus<-tm_map(corpus,content_transformer(removeSpace)) #remove multiple space
 }
 
sample_data_clean <- clean_corpus(sample_data_c)

Feature Extraction by Term Document Matrix(TDM)

Here various N-grams are created and made into their respective term document matrix and later combined into a matrix, so as to better visualize the relationship between words in the Exploratory Analysis.

Uni-Gram TDM

Uni_Tokenizer <- function(x){
  NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 1, max = 1))
}
sample_data_tdm1 <- TermDocumentMatrix(sample_data_clean, control = list(tokenize = Uni_Tokenizer))
dim(sample_data_tdm1)
## [1] 46049     3

Bi-Gram TDM

bi_Tokenizer <- function(x){
  NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 2, max = 2))
}

sample_data_tdm2 <- TermDocumentMatrix(sample_data_clean, control = list(tokenize = bi_Tokenizer))
dim(sample_data_tdm2)
## [1] 199341      3

Tri-Gram TDM

tri_Tokenizer <- function(x){
  NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 3, max = 3))
}
sample_data_tdm3 <- TermDocumentMatrix(sample_data_clean, control = list(tokenize = tri_Tokenizer))
dim(sample_data_tdm3)
## [1] 278586      3

Summary

Uni-gram analysis showed obvius results that the must common words are articles. Bi-gram analysis is not also informative the most frequent constructions are analouguesof english “it is”, “this is” or “there is”. Only tri-gram analysis gives significant information. This implies that N-gram analysis with Ngreater than 2must be implemented.
